04189nam a22005415i 9780226365312DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263653127 a10.7208/97802263653122doi  a(DE-B1597)524402  a(OCoLC)1024191227  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB53 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1012231 aHampe, Michael, eauthor.10aWhat Philosophy Is For /cMichael Hampe. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the American Edition -- tONE. Asserting, Narrating, Educating -- tTWO. Maieutic and Academic Philosophy -- tTHREE. Life, Subjectivity, Assimilation -- tFOUR. The Life of Assertive Beings, Linguistic Dissidence -- tFIVE. Ordinary Language, Theories, and Explanations -- tSIX. The Ordinary and Its Truth -- tSEVEN. Expertocracy and the Education of Individuals -- tEIGHT. Freedom, Necessity, Creativity -- tNINE. Reacting to the World -- tTEN. Telling Stories about Assertions and Arguments -- tELEVEN. Concreteness and Critique -- tTWELVE. Arriving at the End of Asserting -- tEpilogue to the History of Philosophy -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex of Personal Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the state of philosophy today, and what might it be tomorrow? With What Philosophy Is For, Michael Hampe answers these questions by exploring the relationships among philosophy, education, science, and narrative, developing a Socratic critique of philosophical doctrines. Philosophers generally develop systematic theories that lay out the basic structures of human experience, in order to teach the rest of humanity how to rightly understand our place in the world. This "scientific" approach to philosophy, Hampe argues, is too one-sided. In this magnum opus of an essay, Hampe aims to rescue philosophy from its current narrow claims of doctrine and to remind us what it is really for-to productively disillusion us into clearer thinking. Hampe takes us through twenty-five hundred years of intellectual history, starting with Socrates. That archetype of the philosophical teacher did not develop strict doctrines and rules, but rather criticized and refuted doctrines. With the Socratic method, we see the power of narration at work. Narrative and analytical disillusionment, Hampe argues, are the most helpful long-term enterprises of thought, the ones most worth preserving and developing again. What Philosophy Is For is simultaneously an introduction, a critique, and a call to action. Hampe shows how and why philosophy became what it is today, and, crucially, shows what it could be once more, if it would only turn its back on its pretensions to dogma: a privileged space for reflecting on the human condition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aPhilosophyxStudy and teaching. 4aSocratic method. 4acritique. 4ahuman condition. 4aphilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aWinkler, Michael.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226365312423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226365312.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles